LINE.Text: The U.S. will have more than 1.2 million job openings in science, technology, engineering and math
(STEM)-related occupations by 2018. These include scientists, doctors, software developers and
engineers. Yet, there will be a significant shortage of qualified college graduates to fill these careers.
For the U.S. to succeed and continue to play a leadership role in addressing tough global challenges,
we must do a better job of engaging students in these subjects and encouraging them to pursue
careers in STEM-related fields. Here is a look at how early education plays a part in inspiring students
to seek a higher education in STEM and what motivates students to pursue STEM-related fields. 1
The U.S. ranks 25th out of 30 in an international assessment of high schoolers' performance in math.
The U.S. Department of Labor has projected that by 2018, the U.S. will have more than
1.2 million job openings in STEM fields.
